The best approach is to adopt the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already covers `File.*` and `Directory.*`.

### 1. Install

```bash
dotnet add <YourProject> package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject and use

```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDir(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data.txt", new MockFileData("hello") }
});
mockFs.AddDirectory("/mydir");

var svc = new MyService(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("hello", svc.Load("/data.txt"));
Assert.True(svc.EnsureDir("/mydir"));
```

**Why this over a custom wrapper?** `System.IO.Abstractions` wraps the entire `System.IO` surface — you won't need to extend it as you discover more static calls. `MockFileSystem` gives you an in-memory filesystem for tests with no custom mocking needed.

